  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells serve several important functions in plants:\n\n1. Structural support\n- Provide mechanical strength and rigidity to plant tissues\n- Help plants maintain their shape and stand upright\n- Support stems, leaves, and other plant structures\n\n2. Protection\n- Contribute to plant defense by creating a tough, thick cell wall\n- Help protect plant tissues from mechanical damage\n\n3. Load-bearing\n- Enable plants to withstand external forces like wind and gravity\n- Distribute mechanical stress across plant tissues\n\n4. Transport\n- Can form part of the vascular tissue system\n- Help in conducting water and nutrients in some plant structures\n\n5. Maturation\n- Often develop after plant tissues have stopped growing\n- Typically have thick, lignified cell walls that provide additional strength\n\nThere are two main types of sclerenchyma cells:\n- Fibers: Long, narrow cells that provide tensile strength\n- Sclereids: Shorter, more irregularly shaped cells that provide rigidity\n\nThese cells are particularly important in mature plant tissues and play a crucial role in plant structural integrity and mechanical support.",
